A typical HTTP request:
GET / HTTP/1.1  - The first '/' sign indicates the path where the resource is stored on the web server
Host: developer.mozilla.com - headers
Accept-language: en - headers

A typical HTTP response:
HTTP/1.1 200 OK - HTTP version and status code
xxx - other information

Status codes:
Informational: 100 - 199
Successful: 200 - 299
Redirection: 300 - 399
Client error: 400 - 499
Server error: 500 - 599

Commonly used HTTP methods:
GET - retrieve
POST - send
PUT - update
DELETE - remove

HTTP request can also include an optional request body, usually with the POST and PUT methods to transmit data:
e.g. 
POST /users HTTP/1.1
Host: example.com

{
 "key1":"value1",
 "key2":"value2",
 "array1":["value3","value4"]
}
